Liquidated Firm Statistics

Introduction

Liquidated Total (Number) is the number of firms which are gone out of business and their assets sold. This is mostly related to the economic crisis. If the purchasing power of the society decrease, than people donât spend us much. This will directly affects the profit of the business. If the business cannot make enough profit through sales or the services that they provided, they had to shut down. During the economic crisis exchange rates will increase, the prices are higher which means the price index increase. Also the interest will be increased by TCMB to stop the increase in the currencies. Thatâs why I will also examine dollar rates and price index. My assumption is the peaks of these parameters will match the increases in the liquidated firms.

As liquidation also means that the business cannot pay their obligations when they are due. The interest rates for the business may effect the payment. If the interest rates are high, than it is possible for many company to not be able to pay their debts. The interest rates will be examined.

I also assumed that there is a reverse relationship between opened business and closed ones. If the economy is good than the new firms will be established and if the economy is shaking not many firms will be willing to enter the system. I expect to see a negative relationship.

As another regressor, I took the total Capital of Liquidated Companies. I expect a really high correlation between the number of liquidated firms and liquidated capital.

I will make a time series regression, so I will check for seasonality and general trend. I am expecting a see seasonality as year ends is critical for accounting activities.

I will examine the autocorrelation of the target variable. For the April, I wonât have some of my regressors value, thatâs why I will use 1 month lagged versions of the variables. To decide the best model. I may use target values lagged data if it results well. I will check correlations, try to avoid multicollinearity, errors distribution and graphs. I will end up the model which gives me the highest adjusted R square.

My guess is on April, 1175 business will be liquidated.

CONCLUSION

My assumption on the trends and distribution of liquidated companies were not quite in the way that I expected. The regressor that I initially used has a great multicollinerity so I had to eliminate some data. My data has a monthly seasonality which helped me deeply by constructing my model. As I do not have some of my regressor variables for April I had to use the lagged version. Also, to improve the prediction of my model, I added the lagged variable itself and use it as a predictor. This solves the problem of autocorrelation for the regressors. However, at the end model I cannot have a normal distribution of the residuals and had to use it any way.

I build a model and improved it than compare the adjusted R quared results. In the final model we use Monthly trend, the lagged version of log liquidate variable, opened number of business and total liquidated capital. Month 12 has a positive effect on the model, which is an important characteristics of the model.

In the end I made my estimation as 1175 and I will compare it to the actual number when the statistics are announced.
